\end{frame}

% =========================
% Slide 8: Mechanism details that matter in practice
% =========================
\begin{frame}{Implementation details can change outcomes}
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Priorities and tie-breaking} (common in school choice):
  \begin{itemize}
    \item coarse priorities $\Rightarrow$ many ties;
    \item single vs multiple tie-breakers can affect perceived fairness and welfare.
  \end{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Cutoff / price-like structure}:
  \begin{itemize}
    \item DA admits a \textbf{cutoff} interpretation (threshold scores determine feasible choice sets).
    \item Helps connect matching to \textbf{price theory} and supports empirical work.
  \end{itemize}
  \item Practical principle: specify the mechanism \textbf{down to the last rule} (timing, messages, constraints).
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

% =========================
% Slide 9: Empirics (how we learn from data)
% =========================
\begin{frame}{Empirical agenda: estimate preferences, run counterfactuals}
\begin{itemize}
  \item Structural empirics parallels IO discrete choice:
  \begin{itemize}
    \item random utility models using rank lists, observed matches, or both;
    \item handle strategic reporting (harder under non-strategy-proof mechanisms).
  \end{itemize}
  \item Goal: quantify \textbf{trade-offs} and predict effects of alternative designs.
  \item Typical workflow:
  \begin{enumerate}
    \item model environment + mechanism constraints;
    \item estimate preferences / priority structure;
    \item simulate counterfactual mechanisms/policies and welfare impacts.
  \end{enumerate}
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

% =========================
% Slide 10: Takeaways
% =========================
\begin{frame}{Key takeaways}
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Market design studies \textbf{how rules allocate scarce resources} (often without prices).
  \item IO connection: diagnosing failures + fixing them requires \textbf{institutional detail}.
  \item Canonical mechanisms (DA, TTC, etc.) come with \textbf{sharp property trade-offs}.
  \item Empirics is essential: preference estimation + counterfactuals guide real reforms.
\end{enumerate}
\vspace{0.6em}
{\footnotesize Reference: Agarwal, N. \& Budish, E. (2021), ``Market Design'', NBER WP 29367.}
\end{frame}

